                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d289">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.857Ea3</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-04-01T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 1, 1916, 4 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2874. The Department is informed that on March 28 the British steamer <hi
                        rend="italic">Eagle Point</hi> with Americans on board was torpedoed after
                    surrender while bound from St. Johns, New Brunswick, to Cherbourg, and that the
                    persons on board were left in two small boats in a heavy sea with a stormy wind
                    blowing, 130 miles south of Queenstown. Please make immediate inquiry of the
                    German Government as to whether this vessel was torpedoed by a submarine
                    belonging to Germany or its allies. A prompt reply is expected.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
